rtford, Hertfordshire, England":"Hertford, Hertfordshire, Anglie, United Kingdom"},"da":{"1406–1443":"1406–1443","1421–1481":"1421–1481","1395–1461":"1395–1461","1395–1468":"1395–1468","1415–1500":"1415–1500","1380–1450":"1380–1450","1381–1480":"1381–1480","1450":"1450","1461":"1461","1395":"1395","1481":"1481","1480":"1480","1381":"1381","1380":"1380","1415":"1415","1468":"1468","1500":"1500","1415/1416":"1415","1443":"1443","1421":"1421","1406":"1406","Hertford, Hertfordshire, England":"Hertford, Hertfordshire, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"1406–1443":"1406–1443","1421–1481":"1421–1481","1395–1461":"1395–1461","1395–1468":"1395–1468","1415–1500":"1415–1500","1380–1450":"1380–1450","1381–1480":"1381–1480","1450":"1450","1461":"1461","1395":"1395","1481":"1481","1480":"1480","1381":"1381","1380":"1380","1415":"1415","1468":"1468","1500":"1500","1415/1416":"1415","1443":"1443","1421":"1421","1406":"1406","Hertford, Hertfordshire, England":"Hertford, Hertfordshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1406–1443":"1406–1443","1421–1481":"1421–1481","1395–1461":"1395–1461","1395–1468":"1395–1468","1415–1500":"1415–1500","1380–1450":"1380–1450","1381–1480":"1381–1480","1450":"1450","1461":"1461","1395":"1395","1481":"1481","1480":"1480","1381":"1381","1380":"1380","1415":"1415","1468":"1468","1500":"1500","1415/1416":"1415","1443":"1443","1421":"1421","1406":"1406","Hertford, Hertfordshire, England":"Hertford, Hertfordshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Matthew","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Scottish: from the Middle English personal name <i>Ma(t)thew</i>, a vernacular form of the Greek New Testament name <i>Matthias</i>, <i>Matthaios</i>, which is ultimately from the Hebrew personal name <i>Matityahu</i> ‘gift of God’. This was taken into Latin as <i>Mat(t)hias</i> and <i>Matthaeus</i> respectively, the former being used for the twelfth apostle (who replaced Judas Iscariot) and the latter for the author of the first Gospel. In many European languages this distinction is reflected in different name forms. The commonest vernacular forms of the personal name, including English <i>Matthew</i>, Old French <i>Matheu</i>, Spanish <i>Mateo</i>, Italian <i>Matteo</i>, Portuguese <i>Mateus</i>, Catalan and Occitan <i>Mateu</i> are generally derived from the form <i>Matthaeus</i>. In North America, the English form of the surname has absorbed cognates from other languages, including German   Matthias  , Greek   Mathias   and <b>Mattheos</b>, Assyrian/Chaldean   Matti  , Czech <b>Matěj</b>, Slovak, Croatian, and Slovenian   Matej  . The name <i>Matthew</i> is also found among Christians in southern India (compare   Mathai  ), but since South Indians traditionally do not have hereditary surnames, the southern Indian name was in most cases registered as such only after immigration of its bearers to the US. Compare   Mathew  , see also   Matthews  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Maat","meanings":["Dutch:","from the personal name <i>Maat</i>, a short form of <i>Mathias</i> (see   Matthew  ) or, with loss of <i>-r-</i>, of   Martin  .","(<b>Van der Maat</b>): topographic name from <i>maat</i>, <i>made</i> ‘hayfield, meadow’."]},{"name":"Maciej","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Polish Ludwik, Wladyslaw.","Polish: from the personal name <i>Maciej</i>, from Latin <i>Matthaeus</i> (see   Matthew  )."]},{"name":"Macias","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Juan, Jesus, Manuel, Carlos, Raul, Francisco, Luis, Mario, Ruben, Jorge, Roberto.  Portuguese Paulo, Valentim.","Spanish (<b>Macías</b>) and Portuguese: from a variant of the personal name <i>Matías</i> (see   Matthew  )."]},{"name":"Maciag","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Polish Zbigniew, Boguslaw, Casimir, Ryszard, Tadeusz, Thadeus.","Polish (<b>Maciąg</b>): from a derivative of the personal name<i>Maciej</i> (see   Matthew  )."]},{"name":"Matthias","meanings":["German: from the personal name <i>Matthias</i> (see   Matthew  ).","English (mainly Wales): learned variant of   Matthew  .","Greek: variant of   Mathias  ."]},{"name":"Macas","meanings":["Hispanic (mainly Ecuador): unexplained.","Lithuanian: from the personal name <i>Matas</i> or <i>Motiejus</i>; see   Matthew  .","Czech: from a pet form of the personal name <i>Matěj</i> ‘Matthew’ (see   Matej  )."]},{"name":"Maciel","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Manuel, Francisco, Jesus, Juan, Luis, Carlos, Ignacio, Javier, Jorge, Rafael, Ramon.  Portuguese Adauto, Joao, Paulo.","Portuguese and Galician: possibly froma derivative of <i>maça</i> ‘apple’.","Polish: derivative of the personal name <i>Maciej</i> (see   Matthew  )."]},{"name":"Macik","meanings":["Czech (<b>Macík</b>), Slovak (mainly <b>Macík</b>), and Rusyn (from Slovakia): from the personal name Czech and Slovak <i>Macík</i>, Rusyn <i>Matsyk</i>, pet forms of local equivalents of   Matthew   (see also   Macko   and   Matej  ). Alternatively, a nickname from Slovak <i>macík</i> ‘little bear’.","Slovak (<b>Máčik</b>): nickname from <i>máčik</i> ‘tom cat’. Alternatively, a diminutive of   Mak   ‘poppy’."]},{"name":"Macioce","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Mario, Domenic, Valerio, Angelo, Mauro, Pasquale, Vito.","Italian (southern): perhaps from Sicilian <i>maciuciu</i> ‘of noble principles and high culture’, from Spanish <i>machucho</i> ‘wise, old’. Alternatively, it may derive from an altered form of <i>mazzocchi(a)</i> ‘panicle, corncob’.","Altered form of Polish <i>Maciocha</i>, a derivative of the personal name <i>Maciej</i> (see   Matthew  )."]},{"name":"Maciejewski","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Polish Jerzy, Andrzej, Bogdan, Bronislaus, Casimir, Henryk, Jaroslaw, Kazimierz, Krzysztof, Lucjan, Mariusz, Pawel.","Polish: habitational name for someone from any of various places called Maciejowa, Maciejów, or Maciejowice, all named with the personal name <i>Maciej</i>, Polish equivalent of   Matthew  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert Matthew was born in 1406, his father, Alonzo Adam Mathew, was 26 and his mother, Dora Lee Storm, was 25. He had at least 2 daughters with Margaret Ferch Lleywelyn. He died in 1443, at the age of 37."},"et":{"1406–1443":"1406–1443","1421–1481":"1421–1481","1395–1461":"1395–1461","1395–1468":"1395–1468","1415–1500":"1415–1500","1380–1450":"1380–1450","1381–1480":"1381–1480","1450":"1450","1461":"1461","1395":"1395","1481":"1481","1480":"1480","1381":"1381","1380":"1380","1415":"1415","1468":"1468","1500":"1500","1415/1416":"1415","1443":"1443","1421":"1421","1406":"1406","Hertford, Hertfordshire, England":"Hertford, Hertfordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1406–1443":"1406–1443","1421–1481":"1421–1481","1395–1461":"1395–1461","1395–1468":"1395–1468","1415–1500":"1415–1500","1380–1450":"1380–1450","1381–1480":"1381–1480","1450":"1450","1461":"1461","1395":"1395","1481":"1481","14